      <hedline>
        <hl1>More to Say on 'Pursuit of Less'; Laundry Kept On Going After a Father Died</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alicia Kim letter on Andrew Jacobs' August 27 tribute to laundry owner Peter Chow notes similarities with her own and her immigrant parents' lives (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The column was a story about my family too. I am a graduate of Barnard College with two brothers, one a doctor and one a lawyer. My parents, like Mimi and Peter, not only lost their own careers, social status and hopes for a comfortable life, but their first names as well.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The column was a story about my family too. I am a graduate of Barnard College with two brothers, one a doctor and one a lawyer. My parents, like Mimi and Peter, not only lost their own careers, social status and hopes for a comfortable life, but their first names as well.</p>
        <p>This story may seem old to the many descendants of immigrants who live in places like New York, but it's one that reminds me that my next paid two-week vacation from corporate life will be spent folding clothes.</p>
        <p>ALICIA KIM  Upper East Side</p>
      </block>
